<big>
<!-- jobdesc: Job Description -->

<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->

<h2 id="jobdesc">
NOC Operator Job Description </big></p>
<ul style="font-size:100%";color="009900"><li>	Monitor the training and tracking of troops during their exercises. </li>
<li>	Operate radios and communicate with other staff members to assist with a variety of situations. </li>
<li>	Assist with the scanning in and database entry of soldiers who arrrive at the base. </li>
<li>	Make changes in the database when either asked to or through EDI issue reports. </li>
<li>	Assist with the packaging of data disc from the AAR's (packaging). </li>
<li>	Provide support using communications and tracking for coverage testing. </li>
<li>	Assist other teams (Netconfig, Radio Frequency {RF}, Rangeops, Tac) with anything that they might need during downtime. </li>
</ul>
<font color="9900cc">
<p style="font-size:80%";color="9900cc"></p>
</div>

<!-- Frequently used Linux commands & descriptions -->
<br>
<p id="linux">
<big><center>
Linux v7.6 - Frequently Used Commands & Descriptions
</center></big>
</p>
<ul><small>
<li>	<b><u>cat</u></b> - concatenate - it has three related functions with regard to text files; displaying them, combining copies of them, and creating new ones.</li>
<li>	<b><u>cd</u></b> - change directory.  ex; cd /usr/local/Orion/orion-common.</li>
<li>	<b><u>df</u></b> - disk free - diplay information related to file systems about total and available space.  <i>For more info: $man df.</i> </li>
<li>	<b><u>echo</u></b> - built in <b>command</b> in the bash and C shells that writes its arguments to standard output.  <i>For more info: $man echo.</i> </li>
<li>	<b><u>exit</u></b>  - exit command - exit the shell where it is currently running.  After pressing enter, the terminal will simply close.</li>
<li>	<b><u>find</u></b>  - command-line utility that searches one or more directory trees of a file system, locates files based on some user-specified criteria and applies a user-specified action on each matched file.</li>
<!--
<li>	finger - find information about computer users.  It usually lists the login name, the full name, and possibly other details about the user you are fingering.</li>
-->

<li>	<b><u>grep</u></b>  - <b>g</b>lobal <b>r</b>egular <b>e</b>xpression <b>p</b>rint - command-line utility for searching plain-text data sets for lines that match a regular expression.</li>
<li>	<b><u>head</u></b>  - reads the first 10 lines of any given file name.</li>
<li>	<b><u>history</u></b>  - print out the bash history of the current user to the screen.  Commands are numbered, with old commands at the top and newer commands at the bottom.  The history is stored in the ~/bash_history file by default.</li>
<li>	<b><u>ls</u></b>  - list - Linux shell command that lists information about about files and directories.  Part of the GNU core utilites which are installed on all Linux distributions. </li>
<li>	<b><u>man</u></b>  - manual - interface to the on-line reference manuals.  It provides a detailed view of the command which includes NAME, SYNOPSIS, DESCRIPTION, OPTIONS, EXIT STATUS, RETURN VALUES, ERRORS, FILES, VERSIONS, EXAMPLES, AUTHORS and SEE ALSO.</li>
<li>	<b><u>ping</u></b>  - Ping or Packet Internet Groper - It uses ICMP (Internet Control Message Protocol) to communicate to other devices. </li>
<li>	<b><u>tail</u></b>  - reads the last 10 lines of any given file name.</li>
<li>	<b><u>top</u></b>  - task manager program - displays processor activity of your Linux box (cpu and memory) and also displays tasks managed by kernel in real-time. </li>
<pre>
		PID: It is the task's process id.
		USER: It is the effective user name of the task's owner.
		PR: It is the priority of the task.
		NI: The nice value of a task.  A negative nice value means higher priority, whereas a positive nice value means a lower priority.  Zero in this field simply means priority will not be adjusted in determining a task's dispatchability.
		VIRT: It is the total amount of virtual memory used by a task.
		RES: It is the Resident size, the non-swapped physical memory a task has used.
		SHR: It means the Shared Mem size (kb), the amount of shared memory used by a task.
		%CPU: It shows the CPU usage.  The task's share of the elapsed CPU time since the last screen update, expressed as a percentage of total CPU time.
		%MEM: It shows the Memory usage, a task's currently used share of available physical memory.
		TIME+: CPU Time, the same as 'TIME', but reflecting granularity through hundredths of a second.
		COMMAND: Display the command line used to start a task or the name of associated program.
</pre>
<li>	<b><u>w</u></b>  - provides a <i>quick</i> summary of every user logged into a computer, what each user is currently doing, and what load is imposing on the computer itself. (combines; who, uptime, and ps -a). </li>
<li>	<b><u>who</u></b>  - show who is logged on - displays a list of users who are currently logged into the computer.  The <i>who</i> command is related to the command <i>w</i>, which provides the same information but also displays additional data and statistics.</li>
<li>	<b><u>whoami</u></b>  - in computing, <i>whoami</i> is a command found on most Unix-like operating systems, Intel iRMX 86, every Microsoft Windows operating system since Windows Server 2003, and on ReactOS.  It is a concatenation of the words "Who am I?" and prints the effective username of the current user when invoked.</li>
<br>
<b>Note:</b> You can manage files effectively with <i><b>head, tail</b></i> and <i><b>cat.</i></b></br>
</small></ul>
</font>
<font color="black">
<br>
<p><big>
Terminal: GNOME v3.28.2 - a free and open-source desktop environment for Unix-like operating systems (Linux 7.6).
</big><br>
<u>G</u>NU <u>N</u>etwork <u>O</u>bject <u>M</u>odel <u>E</u>nvironment
</p>

<p>

<big>
  ORION - Running SAIPH & RIGEL
</big></p>

<ul><li>
	System Controller (Saiph - top right). </li>
<li>	Ping Network Towers and Relays (if needed). </li>
<li>	Check Network Statistics, log files (if available) and down time with Network Towers/Relays. </li>
<li>	Check for duplicate Miles using MilesChecker.sh in /usr/local/Orion/orion-common/ save copy in ~/Desktop/Miles-mmddyy-hhmm.csv.</li>
<li>	Check freddies for NON-green.</li>
</ul>
<!-- dailychk: Daily NOC Operator Checklist -->
<br>

<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->

<p id="dailychk">
<font color="FF33BB"><big>
<center>
DAILY NOC OPERATOR CHECKLIST</center></big></p>
<ol><li>
	Check with shift leads for any shift assignments.</li>
<li>	Check white board for info from previous shifts.</li>
<li> 	Entry new entries & verify (verify, then verify again).</li>
<li>	Restart RIGEL & SAIPH & NET STATS page before lanes begin.</li>
<li>	Make detailed notes to shifts in NOC log.</li>
<li>	Check ALL NET STATS and RELAYS at least hourly & report to RF any down status.</li>
<li>	Use sign-out sheet for Fredi's, vehicles, equipment & radios.</li>
<li>	Check with TAC for lane tracking daily & fill out sheets while tracking units running lanes.</li>
<li>	Get list of Take Home Packages (THP's) from TAC & create with duplicates as requested.</li>
<li>	Verify all entities in Saiph with range ops tracking issue report.</li>
<li>	Police trash, sweep & mop as needed.  Trash to dumpster.</li>
<li>	Assist, as needed, anyone who comes into NOC seeking assistance.  Refer to shift lead.</li>
<li>	Write any cross info on white board for next shift(s).</li>
</ol>
<br>
