<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->

<!-- C-I-T-K-M: Check Definitions -->
<p id="citkm"><big>
<font color="0099CC">
<center>
<b>C-I-T-K-M DEFINITIONS</b></p>
</center>
</big>
<font size="3">
  <b><u>C = Comm</u></b>
    <blockquote>
      <font color="grey";size="75%">C-Grey:</font>  Device is not in Comms (Either not turned on or not working)<br>
      <font color="red">C-Red:</font>   Device has log/is out of Comms (Dense vegetation or inside building)<br>
      <font color="green">C-Green:</font> Device is communicating.</br>
    </blockquote>
<br>
  <b><u>I = Initialization</u></b></br>
    <blockquote>
      <font color="grey">I-Grey:</font>  Device has not been initialized (Either not turned on or not working)<br>
      <font color="red">I-Red:</font>   Device has failed initialization (Wrong Network ID or not turned on)<br>
      <font color="green">I-Green:</font> Device has initialized and is working properly.<br>
    </blockquote>
<br>
  <b><u>T = Tracking</u></b></br>
    <blockquote>
      <font color="grey">T-Grey:</font>  Device is not GPS tracking (Either not turned on or not working)<br>
      <font color="red">T-Red:</font>   Device is not GPS tacking (Dense vegetation or inside building)<br>
      <font color="green">T-Green:</font> Device was GPS tracking properly.<br>
    </blockquote>
<br>
  <b><u>K = Kill (Life Status)</u></b></br>
    <blockquote>
      <font color="grey">K-Grey:</font>  Device has no life status (Either not turned on or not working)<br>
      <font color="red">K-Red:</font>   Device has been Miles killed (Device is destroyed)<br>
      <font color="green">K-Green:</font> Device is Alive.<br>
    </blockquote>
<br>
  <b><u>M = Miles Status</u></b></br>
    <blockquote>
      <font color="grey">M-Grey:</font>  Device has no Miles paired (Device and Miles are not turned on or not working)<br>
      <font color="red">M-Red:</font>   Device and Miles do not have a proper PID number<br>
      <font color="green">M-Green:</font> Device and Miles have proper PID and can produce and receive shotlines.<br>
    </blockquote>
<br>
  <b><u>Miles Shot/Hit Definitions</u></b></br>
    <blockquote>
      Paired dots with a line means message received from both devices and produced a "shotline".  This will show which devices are associated with the reported PIDs.<br>
      <br>
      A single dot means that the system received a message that reported a shot.  There may be a hit but it won't be from the same device that shot.  Miles shots are reported by who was hit.<br>
      <br>
      An animated white circle means the system received a message that an entity was hit.  If one has an improper PID, a shotline may not show but there will be a hit.<br>
      <br>
      The color of the dots and lines are determined by what group the device is under.  (Blue = Friendly, Red = Hostile and Grey = Unknown).
    </blockquote>
</font>
<br>

<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->

<!-- dthp: Creating a DVD Take Home Package -->

<font color="3333FF">  <!-- blue -->
<p id="dthp"><p><b><big><center>
<b><big>
CREATING A DVD TAKE HOME PACKAGE (DTHP)</center></big></b></p>
<ol>
<li>  Click <b>Applications</b> > <b>Orion</b> ><b> Take Home Package Builder</b><br>  With information provided by the TAC chief or AARPTL, create each DTHP as follows;</br>
<li>  Select the appropriate package <br></li>
	(For example, TAC2.local-15 is the 15th package created by TAC2. The timestamp is at the front of the filename).</br></li>
<li>  Click <b>Create Package</b> (bottom button).<br>
   While process is running, take a blank CD and use a fine Sharpie to write the TAC line info on the disk (ex; TAC 3) unit name, date/time of lane, lane number and type of exercie (ex; company attack).</li>
<li>  Put the disk in the PROPER client server CD slot
<li>  Insert an unused DVD with the XCTC exercise information pre-printed on it.</li>
<li>  Click <b>Burn</b> in the lower right-hand corner of the screen.</li>
<li>  Once the Properties screen pops up, verify the proper boxes have been selected.</li>
<li>  Click <b>Burn</b> again.</li>
<li>  Take the DVD (now the DTHP's master copy) and, per the network supervisors guidance, create copies using the DVD duplicator.
<br>  Note: Some packages are too large to fit on one (1) master.  They will have two (2) packages on the same line (ex; TAC 1-51, 1-52) meaning two master disks will be needed.<br>
<br>  <b>EACH MASTER MUST BE CHECKED!!! (See Next Paragraph; CHECKING PACKAGES)</b><br>
</ol>
<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->

<br>
<!-- chkpkg: Check Package -->

<font color="ff6200">
<p id-"chkpkg";style="font-size=200%">  <!-- medium brown -->

<big><b><center>CHECKING PACKAGES</center></b></big></p>
<ol style="font-size=100%; margin-left: 10px"><br>
Note:  Use one of the laptops available.  Check with your Lead or FAE to see which laptop can be used.<br><br>
<li>  Click <b>Open Folder</b> to review files in FLEXTRAIN GUMP.</li>
<li>  Double-click <b>Setup</b> and set destination to <b>Desktop</b> if needed.</li>
<li>  Click <b>Install</b> ...wait...</li>
<li>  Once installed, Double-click <b>"FLEXTRAIN"</b> using the Desktop Icon. <br>
	Leave the Logger Running when the info box pops up.</li>
<li>  Verify Rigel is Open.  If not, open it.</li>
<li>  Check ALL annotations using the left tab.  Verify are populated, markers are in place and on the time line.  Verify pegs and vehicle icons in the map.<br>
	You will have to change units for ALL the annotations to show (bottom middle annotations box, if multiple units). </li>
<b><font color="FF0000"> MAKE SURE IT'S ALL THE WAY FROM BEGINNING TO END!!!</b></font color>
<li>  After you finish, close the program, take out CD, put Yellow stickie on it.  Keep with rest of the Masters (ask where).</li>
<li>  You MUST Uninstall each disk before checking in a new one.  OR, the files will be CORRUPT from the old disk info.</li>
<li>  <b>Start > Control Panel > Programs and Features</b><br>
	Right-click <b>"FLEXTRAIN"</b><br>
	Click <b>UNINSTALL<b><br>
	Now, ready for next disk.
</ol>
</p>
